<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TITLE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding &amp; Editing Lights
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to create a new light file, open an existing light file, add lights to the map, and edit existing light entries.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- STARTING A LIGHT FILE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Starting a Light File
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To begin editing lights, either open an existing light file or create a new one.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Open Existing Light File
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+O)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Opens an existing
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.lgt</Run>
        light file for editing.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        New Lights
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+N)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Creates a new blank light file.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_open_file.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Opening an existing light file is the easiest way to learn how Urban Chaos levels use lights.
                    You can inspect the original light positions, ranges, colours, and height values before creating your own.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- OPENING A MAP -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Opening the Associated Map
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you start a new light file, the editor begins with a blank canvas and no map loaded.
        For easier editing, open the map file that the light file will be used with.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can open a map by pressing the <Bold>Open Map</Bold> shortcut button in the top bar,
        or by using:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        File → Open Map
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+Shift+O)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Loads an Urban Chaos map file so lights can be placed visually against cell textures,
        buildings, objects, and other map features.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_open_map.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    A light file can still be edited without a map, but placing lights is much easier when the matching map is loaded.
                    The map view gives you a clear reference for streets, rooftops, interiors, buildings, and light-emitting objects.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- ADDING A LIGHT -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding a New Light
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once a map is loaded, select the <Bold>Lights List</Bold> tab and press the
        <Bold>Add Light</Bold> button in the bottom-right of the list. The Add Light button is
        shown as a plus symbol.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_add_button.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        Pressing this button opens the <Bold>Add Light Window</Bold>. This window lets you define
        the initial properties of the light before placing it on the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,2">
        In the Add Light Window, you can set:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The light's <Bold>range</Bold>, from
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">0</Run>
                to
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">255</Run>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The light's <Bold>RGB colour</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                A live <Bold>colour preview swatch</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The light's <Bold>height</Bold> in QWorld pixels.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_add_window.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- LIGHT HEIGHT -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,2">
        Setting the Light Height
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Light height is entered in <Bold>QWorld pixels</Bold>. In Urban Chaos scale,
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">256</Run>
        pixels is equal to one storey.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        You can type a precise height into the <Bold>Total Px</Bold> box, or use the shortcut
        buttons to quickly move the light up or down by one storey:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph Margin="24,6,0,0">
        <Bold Foreground="#E8B84B">+256</Bold> — raises the light by one storey.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,2,0,0">
        <Bold Foreground="#E8B84B">-256</Bold> — lowers the light by one storey.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Use higher Y values for lights placed above the ground, such as street lamps, windows, rooftops,
                    signs, or lights attached to elevated objects.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PLACING THE LIGHT -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Placing the Light on the Map
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        After setting the colour, range, and height, press <Bold>OK</Bold> in the Add Light Window.
        The light is then loaded into the placement buffer.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Move the mouse over the map and click the position where the light should appear.
        The editor creates the new light entry at that map location.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_place_on_map.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    The light is not placed immediately when you press OK. It is first loaded into the placement buffer,
                    then created when you click a location on the map.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SELECTING LIGHTS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Selecting Lights
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A light can be selected in two ways:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select the light entry from the <Bold>Lights List</Bold> table.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the light directly on the visual map display.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The selected light can then be edited, deleted, copied, or used as the source for a paste operation.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_select_light.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_light_selected_on_map.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- EDITING LIGHTS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Editing a Light
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once a light is selected, it can be opened for editing in any of the following ways:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Double-click the light on the map.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Double-click the light entry in the Lights List.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the <Bold>Edit Light</Bold> button at the bottom of the list. This button is shown as a pencil icon.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Editing a light allows you to adjust its range, RGB colour, height, and other light properties.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_edit_light.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- DELETING LIGHTS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Deleting a Light
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To remove a light, select it first, then either press the <Bold>Delete Light</Bold> button
        at the bottom of the Lights List or press the <Bold>Delete</Bold> shortcut key.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The Delete Light button is shown as a waste basket icon.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_delete_light.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">⚠ Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Deleted lights are removed from the active light file. Save a copy before making large changes
                    if you want to preserve the original lighting setup.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- COPYING AND PASTING LIGHTS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Copying &amp; Pasting Lights
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Lights can be copied and pasted to quickly create similar light entries. This is useful
        when placing repeated lights, such as street lamps, hallway lights, windows, or lights
        with the same colour and range.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Copy Light
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+C)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Select a light from the list or map, then press <Bold>Ctrl+C</Bold> or the Copy button.
        The Copy button is shown as a clipboard icon.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">
        Paste Light
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+V)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Pastes the copied light. When using the <Bold>Ctrl+V</Bold> shortcut, the copied light is
        pasted at the current mouse pointer position on the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph Margin="24,6,0,0">
        When using the Paste button, the copied light is pasted near the edge of the visible screen.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/adding_lights_copy_paste.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    For accurate placement, use Ctrl+V while the mouse is positioned exactly where you want the copied light to appear.
                    This is usually faster and more precise than using the Paste button.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- WORKFLOW SUMMARY -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The usual workflow for adding lights is:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Open an existing
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.lgt</Run>
                file with <Bold>Ctrl+O</Bold>, or create a new light file with <Bold>Ctrl+N</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Open the associated map with <Bold>Ctrl+Shift+O</Bold> or the Open Map button.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select the <Bold>Lights List</Bold> tab.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Press the <Bold>Add Light</Bold> button.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the light's colour, range, and height.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Press <Bold>OK</Bold> to load the light into the placement buffer.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the map position where the light should be created.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select, edit, copy, paste, or delete lights as needed.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- NEXT STEPS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Next Steps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        After learning how to add and edit individual lights, continue to the
        <Bold>Map Properties</Bold> section for a detailed explanation of ambient lighting,
        renderer lighting values, prim lighting, and global light file settings.
    </Paragraph>

</FlowDocument>
